<DOC><DOCNO> AP900515-0090 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-90 1216EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-France-Mosque     05-15 0261</FIRST><SECOND>AM-France-Mosque,0267</SECOND><HEAD>Mayor Charged With Ordering Demolition of Mosque</HEAD><DATELINE>LYON, France (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A town mayor was charged with interferingwith religious freedom for ordering the demolition of a wing of anabandoned factory that was being used as a mosque.   Gerard Dezempte, mayor of Charvieu-Chavagneux in eastern France,maintained his innocence during Monday's court hearing in Lyon. Hesaid he assigned a bulldozer to demolish the north wing of thebuilding, and that it accidentally razed the south wing.   Five people were sleeping in the wing when the bulldozer arrivedAugust 16 at 7 a.m. and began the demolition. One of the occupantswas slightly wounded.   The local Moslem community accused Dezempte of racism andrejected his claim that the demolition was accidental. InteriorMinister Pierre Joxe sided with the Moslems, expressing theSocialist government's disapproval of the mayor. Dezempte is amember of the conservative Rally for the Republic party.   The manager of the demolition company, Felix Deschanoz, and hisson, Franck, who drove the bulldozer, also were charged Monday withcomplicity in the unlawful destruction of property and interferencein the practice of religion.   Shortly after the demolition, the bulldozer was set afire, andfires later broke out at the mayor's office and a municipalgymnasium. Dezempte, who had opposed the establishment of a mosquein the town, described the fires as ``terrorist attacks.''   In late August, the mayor and the head of a local Islamiccultural association signed an accord providing new premises for amosque.   The case against the mayor was adjourned until next month.</TEXT></DOC>